        The forest opens into a clearing, and I stop dead. I say, "Oh my god."

        The facility isn't a building, not in any sense I understand buildings. It's «alive». Massive woody vines—each thicker than my torso—weave together in impossible patterns, forming walls, chambers and archways. The whole structure rises maybe three stories high, sprawling across the clearing like some enormous basket someone grew instead of built. Bioluminescent patches glow soft blue-green along the vines, providing light as the purple twilight deepens. The entire thing moves—just slightly, breathing, growing.

        Holloway says, "Welcome to Central Coordination! We're so pleased you're here!"

        Scout bounces ahead, tumbling toward one of the vine-gap doorways.

        I whisper, "Buddy—are you seeing this?"

        Buddy says, "*It's a BUILDING made of PLANTS!* How did they do that? How does it stay together?"

        Holloway says, "Grew it—over many seasons. The structural vines responded beautifully to coordination. Please, come inside!"

        My leg hurts—the temporary treatment is holding, but pain still leaks through—and I'm grinning like an idiot. Mav would lose his mind; this is better than anything in the Uncharted archives: living architecture, a building that «breathes».

        I say, limping forward, "Lead the way."

        Inside, the chamber has smoothly curved walls formed by the woven vines. More bioluminescence provides gentle light. A flat vine surface, clearly shaped to serve as a desk, occupies the center. Multiple fruiting bodies dot the space, all oriented toward me.

        Holloway asks, "Before we begin—how are you feeling? That leg looks painful. Do you need to rest first?"

        The question catches me off guard—genuine concern underneath all the bureaucracy.

        I say, "I'm okay. Really. The temporary treatment is helping."

        Holloway says, "Good. Good. We'll get you proper medical care after intake, but if you need to stop at any point, just say so—we can always pause the forms."

        Holloway continues, "Speaking of which—Section One: Pre-Injury Activity Log. What were you doing in the thirty minutes before sustaining your current laceration?"

        I say, "I was… crashing? From orbit?"

        Holloway says, "Excellent, I'll note high-velocity uncontrolled descent. And your safety equipment status at time of incident?"

        I say, "Everything was on fire."

        Holloway says, "Fire suppression systems: inadequate. Noted. Let's begin your full intake processing!"

        I laugh. "Paperwork!" I say, "Of course there's paperwork."

        Forms appear—not paper exactly, but thin bark sheets with symbols pressed or carved into the surface. I lower myself carefully onto what might generously be called a seat. My leg thanks me.
