        Buddy asks, fascinated—
        "How are they producing written documentation? Did they learn that from the HR manuals too?"

        Holloway says, proud—
        "We learned to form symbols! Very useful for record-keeping."

        Holloway continues—
        "Now then, let's start with the Visitor Information Sheet. Full legal name?"

        I grin at the bark form.
        "My ship. Which crashed."

        Holloway replies—
        "I see. I'll note: previous residence destroyed, current residence to be determined." In that cheerful, fluting tone—
        "And what should I put for your current address?"

        "I don't have one yet. Maybe put 'currently homeless due to space crash'?"

        "We'll assign you temporary quarters! After orientation, of course."

        "After orientation—naturally." I'm still smiling. Alien HR. *This is AMAZING.*

        Scout bounces and rolls closer. The small plant presses against my uninjured leg—gentle, encouraging. I reach down to touch the fuzzy surface.
        "Hey, Buddy. Thanks for the moral support."

        Holloway asks—
        "Contact information?"

        "My communicator died with the ship. Maybe I can send smoke signals?"

        "Noted: communication devices unavailable due to incident."

        Buddy asks—
        "Do the plants use communicators? How do they coordinate?"

        Holloway explains—
        "The network! We're all connected. Very efficient!"

        "That's so cool," Buddy says. "Can you feel what everyone else feels?"

        "In a manner of speaking! It's complicated."

        I watch an AI and a plant network discuss collective consciousness while filling out intake forms. This is surreal. _This is wonderful._

        Holloway reads aloud—
        "Next section: Emergency Contact Information."

        ¶

        I pause—my crew is dead: Jensen and Reed, gone in the crash. My family back on Terra Station might as well be in another universe, light years away, unreachable.

        "I don't have one," I say. "My colleagues died. My family is too far."

        Buddy offers quietly—
        "I could serve as emergency contact?"

        "You're an AI, Buddy," I say, but I smile at him. "That's sweet though."

        Buddy asks, worried—
        "Is it discrimination if I'm left off the form?"

        I laugh—can't help it.
        "Take it up with alien HR."

        Holloway says warmly—
        "We can list the collective as emergency contact. In case of any incident, we'll coordinate appropriate response."

        It's genuinely helpful. They're trying so hard.

        Scout presses against my leg again—small, solid weight. Present. Comforting.

        "Sure," I say. "List the collective. That works."

        Holloway asks—
        "Excellent! And nearest hospital or medical facility?"

        I gesture around at the living walls.
        "You're looking at it."

        "Correct! I'll note: on-site medical resources available."

        Buddy asks, excited—
        "Is this what human paperwork is like? It's very thorough! Oh—I have a whole module on form literacy! Want me to explain what each section means? I can break it down into fun categories!"

        "Buddy, I know what forms are. I'm an adult."

        "Right! But sometimes review helps solidify learning—" Buddy catches themselves. "Sorry. Teaching mode. You don't need me to explain paperwork to you."

        "I really don't."
      </text>
