        "Current injuries?"

        I gesture at my leg, trying to look official, and say—
        "Laceration, approximately fifteen centimeters, partial treatment received, requires follow-up care."

        I'm learning their language—it's kind of fun, actually.

        Holloway asks—
        "Any other injuries from the incident?"

        I say—
        "Bruises, scrapes, possible concussion, exhaustion—you know, standard crash stuff."

        Holloway says—
        "I'll schedule a comprehensive medical evaluation post-orientation."

        I ask—
        "How long is orientation?"

        Holloway replies—
        "Standard protocol is four hours for workplace safety fundamentals!"

        I exclaim—
        "Four hours! *Mav* never had to do *THIS* much prep work." 

        I add, smiling—
        "Workplace safety training for a spaceship crash. This is hilarious."

        I ask about my leg—
        "My leg—is Remedy's treatment holding okay?"

        Buddy reports—
        "Treatment should remain effective for six to eight hours per their notes—you're perfectly scheduled."

        Holloway asks—
        "Allergies?"

        I list what I know. Buddy supplies data from my file—
        "I have your complete records—very thorough."

        Holloway says, pleased—
        "Excellent documentation."

        Holloway asks—
        "Current medications?"

        I say—
        "None—because my ship exploded. No prescription pad in my survival kit."

        Holloway notes—
        "No current prescriptions noted. Understandable given circumstances."

        The pain in my leg pulses, but I grin—this is too weird not to enjoy.

        Holloway announces—
        "Employment history and skills assessment. Current or most recent occupation?"

        I say—
        "I'm not applying for a job—I crashed here. But sure, let's do this."

        Holloway—
        "Information helps us understand your needs and capabilities."

        I grin and say—
        "Cargo specialist. Certified for grade three cargo operations, emergency protocols, basic ship maintenance."

        Buddy adds—
        "You also have excellent organizational skills! And you're very good at counting!"

        I reply—
        "Thanks, Buddy."

        Holloway says, genuinely pleased—
        "Excellent background. Very thorough. This will be very helpful."

        The forms continue—education history, technical skills, hobbies. I tell them about Uncharted, and Buddy excitedly explains about Mav.

        Holloway announces—
        "All intake documentation complete! You're ready for orientation."

        I stand—my leg protests, but I'm ready for what comes next.

        Scout bounces encouragingly toward another chamber—another vine-gap doorway leading deeper into the living structure.

        Holloway, via a fresh fruiting body near the doorway, says—
        "Orientation covers workplace safety protocols, emergency procedures, and facility guidelines."

        I grin and say—
        "Workplace safety training for a spaceship crash. I love it. Let's go."

        Holloway exclaims—
        "We're very excited to have you here, Kira—the first human visitor in many seasons!"
      </text>
